                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">839.415/141b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">White</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="31" xml:id="d152fn31">This telegram was sent at the request
                        of Charles Taussig following his interview the same day with President
                        Roosevelt. Mr. Taussig was chairman of the United States Section,
                        Anglo-American Caribbean Commission, and chairman designate of the United
                        States delegation to the Dominican Centennial.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-14T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 14, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>48. The President desires you to stress to Lescot his personal interest in the
                    border meeting with Trujillo. The President considers it essential that this
                    meeting take place during the Dominican Centennial festivities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
